          <msContents>
            <summary>
              <p>1 fol.; Writing surface: parchment; Shelfmark: KFQ 64; Lines per page: 5; Dimensions: 152 x 228 mm; Qurʾānic Text: Q 40:82-83; Script style: kūfī D.I; Estimated date of production:750-900. </p>
              <p>François Déroche writes about this fragment KFQ 64 (Déroche, <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/QJQEKNSJ" sameAs="QJQEKNSJ" type="zotero">The Abbasid Tradition, London 1992</ref>, p. 70): „22 / Single folio / 9th century AD / 15.2 x 22.8 cm, with 5 lines to the page / <hi rend="italic">Material</hi> Parchment; the recto is the hair side / <hi rend="italic">Text area</hi> 7.5 x 16 cm / <hi rend="italic">Script</hi> A style close to D.I / <hi rend="italic">Accession no</hi>. KFQ 64 / <hi rend="italic">Another fragment from the same Qur’an</hi> / Istanbul, Topkapı Palace Library, MS. EH 30 / (Karatay 1962, no. 53) / The text – verses 82–3 of <hi rend="italic">Sūrat al-muʾmin</hi> (XL) – is written in black ink; there are no diacriticals, except perhaps a red dot (verso, line 2, under a <hi rend="italic">jīm</hi>). The vocalization is indicated by gold dots, a rather unusual occurrence. A gold 3.1.2 device marks the end of every verse.“</p>
              <p>KFQ 64 contains a part of surah 40 (Sūrat Ġāfir or Sūrat al-Muʾmin). The Central Library of the University  of Tehran preserves a fragment from the same codex. Besides the Istanbul fragment, listed by Déroche (EH 30, Karatay 1962, no. 53) another fragment is part of <ref target="https://artmuseum.indiana.edu/collections-online/browse/object.php?number=63.41">Sidney and Lois Eskenazi Museum of Art (Bloomington Indian) shelfmark  63.41</ref>.  </p>
            </summary>
